  <span id="freeText15006270174863363187" style="display:none">Preliminary thoughts: I desperately want to see this performed live.<br /><br />I couldn't believe this was based on a true story at first, but <a href="https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-shi-pei-pu6-2009jul06-story.html" title="it's exactly as mind-boggling as it sounds." rel="nofollow noopener">it remarkably is</a>, which is absolutely insane to me. A French diplomat who falls in love with a Chinese actress and opera singer and embarks on a 20-year relationship, only to discover that his ~exotic oriental butterfly~ is a man... and has been spying on him the whole time? Insane. I fucking love people.<br /><br />Western stereotypical perceptions of China, the East, Asia in general, play a major role not only in the relationship between Gallimard and Song but in the (less-than-)subtextual political aspect of the play. David Henry Hwang also touches on Asian perceptions of the West and the conflicts that naturally arise when two people from very different cultures bring together their preconceived notions of gender roles and societal ideals, topics which would come across as preachy if not for Hwang's unerring comedic, theatrical tone throughout. The unreliable narration also lends an additional delicious layer of deceit and subjectivity atop the already layered story being told. The result was an acerbic, theatrical satire of gender, sexuality, Orientalism, imperialism, misogyny, and the cultural divide that prevents people from viewing those from other cultures as human. Hwang explains in his notes on the play that he heard of the story and was captivated by it, and conceived this play as a sort of reverse <i>Mme Butterfly</i>: Gallimard thinks of himself as Pinkerton and Song as the titular Butterfly, but by the end, when all has been (metaphorically and literally) laid bare, it's made obvious that the positions were the opposite.<br /><br />The obvious question is, of course, "How could he—Gallimard or his real-life counterpart—not <i>tell</i>?" Hwang, through Song, explains briefly that a combination of factors ranging from poor sex education (i.e., Gallimard didn't really know what to expect "down there" with a woman) to racism (i.e., Song pretended to be shy and demure, as was expected of an Oriental woman—Hwang's choice of adjective, not mind—and Gallimard, high off his white saviour fantasy, didn't question it) produced the perfectly simple answer: he didn't want to know, so he didn't. The woman he fell in love with was never a real person but rather a construct born of misogyny, racism, Orientalism, fetishism, toxic masculinity, power fantasies, what-have-you.<br /><br />Hwang masterfully addresses all of these topics—sex, gender, power, Orientalism, fetishisation, romance, desire, manipulation, identity, etc.—weaving together the mechanics of the true story with the allegorical subtext with the plot of the opera <i>Mme Butterfly</i>, after which this play is titled. Song puts on a show of performing the version of submissive, subservient Asian femininity that Gallimard expects and finds appealing:<blockquote>As soon as a Western man comes into contact with the East, he's already confused. The West has sort of an international rape mentality towards the East. [...] The West thinks of itself as masculine—big guns, big industry, big money—so the East is feminine—weak, delicate, poor... but good at art, and full of inscrutable wisdom: the feminine mystique. Her mouth says no, but her eyes say yes. The West believes the East, deep down, wants to be dominated... because a woman can't think for herself. [...] You expect Oriental countries to submit to your guns, and you expect Oriental women to be submissive to your men.</blockquote>It's a performance filtered expertly through a lens that would be hardly different today, with the Western/European/American stereotype of a submissive Asian girlfriend who practically worships her white boyfriend and perpetually speaks/acts like she's in anime (or, realistically, hentai). Gallimard flat-out states that "While we men may all want to kick Pinkerton, very few of us would pass up the opportunity to <i>be</i> Pinkerton": this is the role in which he envisions himself: the white saviour, the hero, the civilised man in love with the exotic foreign butterfly. Song likewise comments, "It's one of your favourite fantasies, isn't it? The submissive Oriental woman and the cruel white man." It's not a love story except that it's a love story between cultural stereotypes and Orientalism.<blockquote>Consider it this way: what would you say if a blond homecoming queen fell in love with a short Japanese businessman? He treats her cruelly, then goes home for three years, during which time she prays to his picture and turns down marriage from a young Kennedy. Then, when she learns he has remarried, she kills herself. Now I believe you should consider this girl to be a deranged idiot, correct? But because it's an Oriental who kills herself for a Westerner—ah!—you find it beautiful.</blockquote>Song states that "[...] when he [Gallimard] finally met his fantasy woman, <i>he wanted more than anything to believe that she was, in fact, a woman</i>. And second, I am an Oriental. And being an Oriental, I could never be completely a man."<br /><br />In conclusion: I desperately want to see this performed live.</span>
